# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: high-level-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Synthesis begins with a high-level specification of the problem, where behavior is generally decoupled from low-level circuit mechanics such as clock-level timing.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Early HLS explored a variety of input specification languages, although recent research and commercial applications generally accept synthesizable subsets of ANSI C/C++/SystemC/MATLAB.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The code is analyzed, architecturally constrained, and scheduled to transcompile from a transaction-level model (TLM) into a register-transfer level (RTL) design in a hardware description language (HDL), which is in turn commonly synthesized to the gate level by the use of a logic synthesis tool.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Verification of the RTL is an important part of the process.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Hardware can be designed at varying levels of abstraction.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The commonly used levels of abstraction are gate level, register-transfer level (RTL), and algorithmic level.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] While logic synthesis uses an RTL description of the design, high-level synthesis works at a higher level of abstraction, starting with an algorithmic description in a high-level language such as SystemC and ANSI C/C++.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The designer typically develops the module functionality and the interconnect protocol.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The high-level synthesis tools handle the micro-architecture and transform untimed or partially timed functional code into fully timed RTL implementations, automatically creating cycle-by-cycle detail for hardware implementation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The (RTL) implementations are then used directly in a conventional logic synthesis flow to create a gate-level implementation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Early academic work extracted scheduling, allocation, and binding as the basic steps for high-level-synthesis.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Scheduling partitions the algorithm in control steps that are used to define the states in the finite-state machine.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Each control step contains one small section of the algorithm that can be performed in a single clock cycle in the hardware.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Allocation and binding maps the instructions and variables to the hardware components, multiplexers, registers and wires of the data path.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] First generation behavioral synthesis was introduced by Synopsys in 1994 as Behavioral Compiler and used Verilog or VHDL as input languages.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The abstraction level used was partially timed (clocked) processes.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Tools based on behavioral Verilog or VHDL were not widely adopted in part because neither languages nor the partially timed abstraction were well suited to modeling behavior at a high level.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] 10 years later, in early 2004, Synopsys end-of-lifed Behavioral Compiler.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Forte Design Systems introduced its Cynthesizer tool which used SystemC as an entry language instead of Verilog or VHDL.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Cynthesizer was adopted by many Japanese companies in 2000 as Japan had a very mature SystemC user community.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The first high-level synthesis tapeout was achieved in 2001 by Sony using Cynthesizer.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Adoption in the United States started in earnest in 2008.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] In 2006, an efficient and scalable "SDC modulo scheduling" technique was developed on control and data flow graphs and was later extended to pipeline scheduling.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] This technique uses the integer linear programming formulation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] But it shows that the underlying constraint matrix is totally unimodular (after approximating the resource constraints).
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Thus, the problem can be solved in polynomial time optimally using a linear programming solver in polynomial time.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] This work was inducted to the FPGA and Reconfigurable Computing Hall of Fame 2022.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The SDC scheduling algorithm was implemented in the xPilot HLS system developed at UCLA, and later licensed to the AutoESL Design Technologies, a spin-off from UCLA.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] AutoESL was acquired by Xilinx (now part of AMD) in 2011, and the HLS tool developed by AutoESL became the base of Xilinx HLS solutions, Vivado HLS and Vitis HLS, widely used for FPGA designs.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The most common source inputs for high-level synthesis are based on standard languages such as ANSI C/C++, SystemC and MATLAB.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] High-level synthesis typically also includes a bit-accurate executable specification as input, since to derive an efficient hardware implementation, additional information is needed on what is an acceptable Mean-Square Error or Bit-Error Rate etc.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] For example, if the designer starts with an FIR filter written using the "double" floating type, before they can derive an efficient hardware implementation, they need to perform numerical refinement to arrive at a fixed-point implementation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The refinement requires additional information on the level of quantization noise that can be tolerated, the valid input ranges etc.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] This bit-accurate specification makes the high level synthesis source specification functionally complete.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Normally the tools infer from the high level code a Finite State Machine and a Datapath that implement arithmetic operations.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] The high-level synthesis process consists of a number of activities.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Various high-level synthesis tools perform these activities in different orders using different algorithms.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Some high-level synthesis tools combine some of these activities or perform them iteratively to converge on the desired solution.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] In general, an algorithm can be performed over many clock cycles with few hardware resources, or over fewer clock cycles using a larger number of ALUs, registers and memories.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Correspondingly, from one algorithmic description, a variety of hardware microarchitectures can be generated by an HLS compiler according to the directives given to the tool.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] This is the same trade off of execution speed for hardware complexity as seen when a given program is run on conventional processors of differing performance, yet all running at roughly the same clock frequency.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Synthesis constraints for the architecture can automatically be applied based on the design analysis.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Interface Synthesis refers to the ability to accept a pure C/C++ description as its input, then use automated interface synthesis technology to control the timing and communications protocol on the design interface.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] This enables interface analysis and exploration of a full range of hardware interface options such as streaming, single- or dual-port RAM plus various handshaking mechanisms.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] With interface synthesis, the designer does not embed interface protocols in the source description.
[src:high-level-synthesis/behavioral-synthesis] Examples might be: direct connection, one line, 2-line handshake, FIFO.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Early development on C to HDL was done by Ian Page, Charles Sweeney and colleagues at Oxford University in the 1990s who developed the Handel-C language.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] They commercialized their research by forming Embedded Solutions Limited (ESL) in 1999 which was renamed Celoxica in September 2000.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] In 2008, the embedded systems departments of Celoxica was sold to Catalytic for $3 million and which later merged to become Agility Computing.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] In January 2009, Mentor Graphics acquired Agility's C synthesis assets.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Celoxica continues to trade concentrating on hardware acceleration to process transactions in the financial sector and other industries.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] C to HDL techniques are most commonly applied to applications that have unacceptably high execution times on existing general-purpose supercomputer architectures.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Examples include bioinformatics, computational fluid dynamics (CFD), financial processing, and oil and gas survey data analysis.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Embedded applications requiring high performance or real-time data processing are also an area of use.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] System-on-chip (SoC) design may also take advantage of C to HDL techniques.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] C-to-VHDL compilers are very useful for large designs or for implementing code that might change in the future.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Designing a large application entirely in HDL may be very difficult and time-consuming; the abstraction of a high level language for such a large application will often reduce total development time.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Furthermore, an application coded in HDL will almost certainly be more difficult to modify than one coded in a higher level language.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] If the designer needs to add new functionality to the application, adding a few lines of C code will almost always be easier than remodeling the equivalent HDL code.
[src:high-level-synthesis/c-to-hdl] Flow to HDL tools have a similar aim, but with flow rather than C-based design.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In computer engineering, **logic synthesis** is a process by which an abstract specification of desired circuit behavior, typically at register transfer level (RTL), is turned into a design implementation in terms of logic gates, typically by a computer program called a *synthesis tool*.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Common examples of this process include synthesis of designs specified in hardware description languages, including VHDL and Verilog.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Some synthesis tools generate bitstreams for programmable logic devices such as PALs or FPGAs, while others target the creation of ASICs.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Logic synthesis is one step in circuit design in the electronic design automation, the others are place and route and verification and validation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The roots of logic synthesis can be traced to the treatment of logic by George Boole (1815 to 1864), in what is now termed Boolean algebra.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In 1938, Claude Shannon showed that the two-valued Boolean algebra can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In the early days, **logic design** involved manipulating the truth table representations as Karnaugh maps.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The Karnaugh map-based minimization of logic is guided by a set of rules on how entries in the maps can be combined.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] A human designer can typically only work with Karnaugh maps containing up to four to six variables.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The first step toward automation of logic minimization was the introduction of the Quine–McCluskey algorithm that could be implemented on a computer.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] This exact minimization technique presented the notion of prime implicants and minimum cost covers that would become the cornerstone of two-level minimization.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Nowadays, the much more efficient Espresso heuristic logic minimizer has become the standard tool for this operation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Another area of early research was in state minimization and encoding of finite-state machines (FSMs), a task that was the bane of designers.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The applications for logic synthesis lay primarily in digital computer design.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Hence, IBM and Bell Labs played a pivotal role in the early automation of logic synthesis.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The evolution from discrete logic components to programmable logic arrays (PLAs) hastened the need for efficient two-level minimization, since minimizing terms in a two-level representation reduces the area in a PLA.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Two-level logic circuits are of limited importance in a very-large-scale integration (VLSI) design; most designs use multiple levels of logic.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Almost any circuit representation in RTL or Behavioural Description is a multi-level representation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] An early system that was used to design multilevel circuits was LSS from IBM.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] It used local transformations to simplify logic.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Work on LSS and the Yorktown Silicon Compiler spurred rapid research progress in logic synthesis in the 1980s.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Several universities contributed by making their research available to the public, most notably SIS from University of California, Berkeley, RASP from University of California, Los Angeles and BOLD from University of Colorado, Boulder.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Within a decade, the technology migrated to commercial logic synthesis products offered by electronic design automation companies.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The leading developers and providers of logic synthesis software packages are Synopsys, Cadence, and Siemens.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Their synthesis tools are Synopsys Design Compiler, Cadence First Encounter and Siemens Precision RTL.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Logic operations usually consist of Boolean AND, OR, XOR and NAND operations, and are the most basic forms of operations in an electronic circuit.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Arithmetic operations are usually implemented with the use of logic operators.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] With a goal of increasing designer productivity, research efforts on the synthesis of circuits specified at the behavioral level have led to the emergence of commercial solutions in 2004, which are used for complex ASIC and FPGA design.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] These tools automatically synthesize circuits specified using high-level languages, like ANSI C/C++ or SystemC, to a register transfer level (RTL) specification, which can be used as input to a gate-level logic synthesis flow.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Typical practical implementations of a logic function utilize a multi-level network of logic elements.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Starting from an RTL description of a design, the synthesis tool constructs a corresponding multilevel Boolean network.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Next, this network is optimized using several technology-independent techniques before technology-dependent optimizations are performed.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The typical cost function during technology-independent optimizations is total literal count of the factored representation of the logic function (which correlates quite well with circuit area).
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Finally, technology-dependent optimization transforms the technology-independent circuit into a network of gates in a given technology.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The simple cost estimates are replaced by more concrete, implementation-driven estimates during and after technology mapping.
[src:high-level-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Mapping is constrained by factors such as the available gates (logic functions) in the technology library, the drive sizes for each gate, and the delay, power, and area characteristics of each gate.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:high-level-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC is applied to system-level modeling, architectural exploration, performance modeling, software development, functional verification, and high-level synthesis.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC is often associated with electronic system-level (ESL) design, and with transaction-level modeling (TLM).
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC is defined and promoted by the Open SystemC Initiative (OSCI — now Accellera), and has been approved by the IEEE Standards Association as IEEE 1666-2011 - the SystemC Language Reference Manual (LRM).
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] The LRM provides the definitive statement of the semantics of SystemC.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] OSCI also provide an open-source proof-of-concept simulator (sometimes incorrectly referred to as the reference simulator), which can be downloaded from the OSCI website.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Although it was the intent of OSCI that commercial vendors and academia could create original software compliant to IEEE 1666, in practice most SystemC implementations have been at least partly based on the OSCI proof-of-concept simulator.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC has semantic similarities to VHDL and Verilog, but may be said to have a syntactical overhead compared to these when used as a hardware description language.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] On the other hand, it offers a greater range of expression, similar to object-oriented design partitioning and template classes.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Although strictly a C++ class library, SystemC is sometimes viewed as being a language in its own right.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Source code can be compiled with the SystemC library (which includes a simulation kernel) to give an executable.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] The performance of the OSCI open-source implementation is typically worse than commercial VHDL/Verilog simulators when used for register transfer level simulation.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC version 1 included common hardware-description language features such as structural hierarchy and connectivity, clock-cycle accuracy, delta cycles, four-valued logic (0, 1, X, Z), and bus-resolution functions.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC version 2 onward focused on communication abstraction, transaction-level modeling, and virtual-platform modeling.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] It also added abstract ports, dynamic processes, and timed event notifications.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC has a notion of a container class called a module.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] This is a hierarchical entity that can have other modules or processes contained in it.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Modules are the basic building blocks of a SystemC design hierarchy.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] A SystemC model usually consists of several modules which communicate via ports.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] The modules can be thought of as a building block of SystemC.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Ports allow communication from inside a module to the outside (usually to other modules) via channels.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC supports resolved and unresolved signals.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Resolved signals can have more than one driver (a bus) while unresolved signals can have only one driver.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Modules have ports through which they connect to other modules.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC supports single-direction and bidirectional ports.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Exports incorporate channels and allow communication from inside a module to the outside (usually to other modules).
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Processes are used to describe functionality.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC provides three different process abstractions to be used by hardware and software designers.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Processes are the main computation elements.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Channels are the communication elements of SystemC.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] They can be either simple wires or complex communication mechanisms like FIFOs or bus channels.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Ports use interfaces to communicate with channels.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Events allow synchronization between processes and must be defined during initialization.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC introduces several data types which support the modeling of hardware.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] SystemC traces its origins to work on Scenic programming language described in a DAC 1997 paper.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] ARM Ltd., CoWare, Synopsys and CynApps teamed up to develop SystemC (CynApps later became Forte Design Systems) to launch it first draft version in 1999.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] The chief competitor at the time was SpecC another C based open source package developed by UC Irvine personnel and some Japanese companies.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] In June 2000, a standards group known as the Open SystemC Initiative was formed to provide an industry neutral organization to host SystemC activities and to allow Synopsys' largest competitors, Cadence and Mentor Graphics, democratic representation in SystemC development.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] The power and energy estimation can be accomplished in SystemC by means of simulations.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Powersim is a SystemC class library aimed to the calculation of power and energy consumption of hardware described at system level.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] To this end, C++ operators are monitored and different energy models can be used for each SystemC data type.
[src:high-level-synthesis/systemc] Simulations with Powersim do not require any change in the application source code.
